<DOC><DOCNO> AP880308-0009 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-08-88 0047EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p BC-MississippiAt-A-Glance     03-08 0223</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Mississippi At-A-Glance,240</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are the methods for pickingdelegates from Mississippi to attend the 1988 Democratic andRepublican national conventions this summer.</TEXT><HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: Bruce Babbitt, Michael Dukakis, RichardGephardt, Albert Gore, Gary Hart, Jesse Jackson, Paul Simon   Pledged delegates: 40   Super delegates: 5   Total: 45   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Saturday, March 19 and Saturday, March 26   All of Mississippi's 40 pledged Democratic National Conventiondelegates will be allocated among presidential candidates inproportion to results of the state primary March 8.</TEXT><HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 8   Candidates filed: George Bush, Bob Dole, Jack Kemp, PatRobertson, Pete du Pont, Alexander Haig   Delegates: 31   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 8   Selection of delegates: Saturday, April 30 and Saturday, May 21   The results of Mississippi's primary govern how its Republicannational convention delegates are allocated among presidentialcandidates.   Three delegates from each of the state's five congressionaldistricts are awarded on a winner-take-all basis to the candidatereceiving the most votes in that district.   The remaining 16 delegates at-large are allocated amongpresidential candidates in proportion to the results of theprimary. Only those candidates receiving at least 10 percent of thevote statewide are eligible to claim national convention delegates.</TEXT></DOC>